Saturation is a region in device operation that is typically avoided in analog circuits because the transistor gain is very low in this region. However, saturation is more commonly encountered in digital circuits, where it provides a well-defined output voltage that represents a logic state.

In saturation, both the emitter-base and collector-base junctions are forward biased. Consequently, the collector-emitter voltage \( V_{CE} \) is quite small, usually in the range of 0.05 to 0.3 V. The carrier concentrations in a saturated npn transistor with uniform base doping are shown in Fig. 1.11. The minority-carrier concentration in the base at the edge of the depletion region is given by (1.28) as

\[
\begin{equation*}
n_{p}\left(W_{B}\right)=n_{p o} \exp \frac{V_{B C}}{V_{T}} \tag{1.59}
\end{equation*}
\]

The graph in Figure 1.11 illustrates the carrier concentration profiles in a saturated npn transistor. It is a spatial distribution graph that shows how the carrier concentration varies across different regions of the transistor: the emitter, base, and collector.

