In Section 1.2.2, the mechanism of avalanche breakdown in a pn junction was detailed. Similar phenomena occur at the base-emitter and base-collector junctions of a transistor, limiting the maximum applicable voltages.

Consider first a transistor in the common-base configuration illustrated in Fig. 1.14a, supplied with a constant emitter current. Typical $I_{C}-V_{C B}$ characteristics for an npn transistor in this setup are depicted in Fig. 1.14b. For $I_{E}=0$, the collector-base junction breaks down at a voltage $B V_{C B O}$, indicating collector-base breakdown with an open emitter. For non-zero $I_{E}$ values, avalanche multiplication effects are evident for $V_{C B}$ values below $B V_{C B O}$. In the example shown, the effective common-base current gain $\alpha_{F}=I_{C} / I_{E}$ exceeds unity for $V_{C B}$ values above approximately 60 V. Operation in this region (but below $B V_{C B O}$) is safe if device power dissipation remains manageable. The principles from Section 1.2.2 apply here, and neglecting leakage currents, the collector current in Fig. 1.14a can be calculated as

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{C}=-\alpha_{F} I_{E} M \tag{1.74}
\end{equation*}
$$

where $M$ is defined by (1.26), thus

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{C}=-\alpha_{F} I_{E} \frac{1}{1-\left(\frac{V_{C B}}{B V_{C B O}}\right)^{n}} \tag{1.75}
\end{equation*}
$$

