The transconductance is defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
g_{m}=\frac{d I_{C}}{d V_{B E}} \tag{1.89}
\end{equation*}
$$

Given that

$$
\Delta I_{C}=\frac{d I_{C}}{d V_{B E}} \Delta V_{B E}
$$

we can express

$$
\Delta I_{C}=g_{m} \Delta V_{B E}
$$

which leads to

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{c}=g_{m} v_{i} \tag{1.90}
\end{equation*}
$$

The value of $g_{m}$ can be determined by substituting (1.35) into (1.89), resulting in

$$
\begin{equation*}
g_{m}=\frac{d}{d V_{B E}} I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{B E}}{V_{T}}=\frac{I_{S}}{V_{T}} \exp \frac{V_{B E}}{V_{T}}=\frac{I_{C}}{V_{T}}=\frac{q I_{C}}{k T} \tag{1.91}
\end{equation*}
$$

Thus, the transconductance varies linearly with the bias current $I_{C}$ and equals $38 \mathrm{~mA} / \mathrm{V}$ for $I_{C}=$ 1 mA at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$, applicable to any bipolar transistor (either $n p n$ or pnp), regardless of size or material ( $\mathrm{Si}, \mathrm{Ge}, \mathrm{GaAs}$ ).

To highlight the constraints of small-signal analysis, an alternative derivation of the previous relation is provided. The total collector current in Fig. 1.17a can be computed using (1.35) as

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{c}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{B E}+v_{i}}{V_{T}}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{B E}}{V_{T}} \exp \frac{v_{i}}{V_{T}} \tag{1.92}
\end{equation*}
$$

However, the collector bias current is

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{C}=I_{S} \exp \frac{V_{B E}}{V_{T}} \tag{1.93}
\end{equation*}
$$

Using (1.93) in (1.92) yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{c}=I_{C} \exp \frac{v_{i}}{V_{T}} \tag{1.94}
\end{equation*}
$$

For $v_{i}<V_{T}$, the exponential in (1.94) can be expanded into a power series,

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{c}=I_{C}\left[1+\frac{v_{i}}{V_{T}}+\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{v_{i}}{V_{T}}\right)^{2}+\frac{1}{6}\left(\frac{v_{i}}{V_{T}}\right)^{3}+\cdots\right] \tag{1.95}
\end{equation*}
$$

The incremental collector current is defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{c}=I_{c}-I_{C} \tag{1.96}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting (1.96) into (1.95) results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
i_{c}=\frac{I_{C}}{V_{T}} v_{i}+\frac{1}{2} \frac{I_{C}}{V_{T}^{2}} v_{i}^{2}+\frac{1}{6} \frac{I_{C}}{V_{T}^{3}} v_{i}^{3}+\cdots \tag{1.97}
\end{equation*}
$$

When $v_{i} \ll V_{T}$, (1.97) simplifies to (1.90), validating the small-signal analysis. The criterion for applying small-signal analysis is thus $v_{i}=\Delta V_{B E} \ll 26 \mathrm{mV}$ at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. Practically, if $\Delta V_{B E}$ is below 10 mV, the small-signal analysis remains accurate to within approximately 10 percent.

