In the forward-active region, the relationship between the base current \(I_{B}\) and the collector current \(I_{C}\) is given by

$$
\begin{equation*}
I_{B}=\frac{I_{C}}{\beta_{F}} \tag{1.47}
\end{equation*}
$$

Small variations in \(I_{B}\) and \(I_{C}\) can be connected using equation (1.47):

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta I_{B}=\frac{d}{d I_{C}}\left(\frac{I_{C}}{\beta_{F}}\right) \Delta I_{C} \tag{1.106}
\end{equation*}
$$

leading to

$$
\begin{equation*}
\beta_{0}=\frac{\Delta I_{C}}{\Delta I_{B}}=\frac{i_{c}}{i_{b}}=\left[\frac{d}{d I_{C}}\left(\frac{I_{C}}{\beta_{F}}\right)\right]^{-1} \tag{1.107}
\end{equation*}
$$

Here, \(\beta_{0}\) represents the small-signal current gain of the transistor. It should be noted that if \(\beta_{F}\) remains constant, then \(\beta_{F}=\beta_{0}\). Typically, the values of \(\beta_{0}\) are similar to those of \(\beta_{F}\), and in later chapters, minimal distinction is made between these parameters. Often, a single value of \(\beta\) is assumed for the transistor and utilized for both AC and DC calculations.

Equation 1.107 links the variation in base current \(i_{b}\) to the corresponding change in collector current \(i_{c}\), and the transistor exhibits a small-signal input resistance defined as

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{\pi}=\frac{v_{i}}{i_{b}} \tag{1.108}
\end{equation*}
$$

Substituting (1.107) into (1.108) results in

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{\pi}=\frac{v_{i}}{i_{c}} \beta_{0} \tag{1.109}
\end{equation*}
$$

Further application of (1.90) in (1.109) yields

$$
\begin{equation*}
r_{\pi}=\frac{\beta_{0}}{g_{m}} \tag{1.110}
\end{equation*}
$$

Therefore, the small-signal input shunt resistance of a bipolar transistor is dependent on the current gain and inversely proportional to \(I_{C}\).

